posts.name: Sumter Link
posts.cooked: Just out of curiosity, do you have an opinion on the PVC vs EPDM insulation material that they offer?  We have used both and never seen a difference, the EPDM is nice because of how flexible it is, but would there be any drawback of significance using one over the other?

posts.name: Rod
posts.cooked:
EPDM is a better choice.  Tougher, higher service temperature.  Much more cut resistant than silicone.

OMG, grasshopper nuts with Nord locks are the Bomb!!  Go get yours!!!

Don‚Äôt be afraid to take your lugs and put a 90 degree bend in them to make the wires dress better.  The pre-bent lugs are excessively expensive and hard to get.  No real difference, no issues at all on any of our batteries built up this way.

posts.name: s-neff
posts.cooked:
I don‚Äôt like telling people to bend their own lugs because I‚Äôm nervous about too tight a radius resulting in tearing the copper instead of bending it - particularly using a bare steel vise, which is what most teams would have access to.

I use a radius from a piece of wood to support the copper, so that the wood mushes before the copper tears. I still get a tighter radius than I really like but haven‚Äôt invested in hard tooling yet.

posts.name: Brett B Bonner
posts.cooked:
Weldingrod1:

EPDM is a better choice.

Second that!  Nicer on batteries and much easier to route as the main power feed in the robot.  It‚Äôs commonly sold as ‚Äúwelding cable‚Äù.

For those making their own from scratch, we‚Äôve often sourced it from Temco Industrial - 6AWG red and black in 50‚Äô lengths are just over $1/ft each and free shipping.  They have shorter lengths at incrementally higher prices, and also larger gauges if you go that direction.

Of course you must have a proper ( true AWG sized ) crimper to make your own cables.  If you don‚Äôt, and don‚Äôt have a team near you that has one and can give you a hand, you‚Äôre much better off with the commercially made ones. These are the most important connections on your robot.

Weldingrod1:

Don‚Äôt be afraid to take your lugs and put a 90 degree bend in them to make the wires dress better. The pre-bent lugs are excessively expensive and hard to get. No real difference, no issues at all on any of our batteries built up this way.

We just bought some 90-degree lugs from Ferrules Direct for $1.10/ea (4AWG) to try the right-angle dressing approach.  They appear to be nice and sturdy but we haven‚Äôt actually assembled a battery with them yet.

I always shied away from DIY lug-bending for fear of inducing metal fatigue, so we never actually tried it. @Weldingrod1 you‚Äôve never had one crack, either initially or after a season of hard use?

posts.name: s-neff
posts.cooked:
bbonner:

you‚Äôve never had one crack, either initially

Not rod, but I remember I cracked at least one during manufacturing‚Ä¶ haven‚Äôt seen any come off damaged at the end of a season. (Total of 50+, so only losing one isn‚Äôt bad, but definitely wouldn‚Äôt tell a novice on Chief to go do it.)

The FerrulesDirect 90¬∞ lug at around $1 is a godsend, I don‚Äôt want to spend my time bending lugs. It was worth it when I could only find $5 Panduit stuff.
